====================================================
NETWORKING BASICS – SYSTEM DESIGN QUICK NOTES
====================================================

🔹 OSI Model (7 Layers)
- Conceptual model for network communication
- Splits networking into layers for abstraction

Layers (Top → Bottom):
7. Application → HTTP, APIs
6. Presentation → Encoding, Encryption
5. Session → Connection management
4. Transport → TCP / UDP
3. Network → IP (routing)
2. Data Link → MAC, frames
1. Physical → Bits, cables

Key Idea:
- Each layer has a specific responsibility
- Helps modular design and debugging :contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 HTTP Request Breakdown

Flow:
Client → DNS → Server → Response

HTTP Request:
- Method → GET, POST, PUT, DELETE
- Headers → metadata
- Body → data (optional)

Response:
- Status code → 200, 404, 500
- Headers + Body

👉 Stateless protocol (no memory between requests)

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Internet Protocol (IP)

- Responsible for addressing + routing packets
- Each device has unique IP address
- Sends packets from source → destination

Key:
- Unreliable (best-effort delivery)
- No guarantee of order or delivery :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 TCP vs UDP (Transport Layer)

TCP:
- Connection-oriented
- Reliable, ordered delivery
- Retransmission + congestion control

UDP:
- Connectionless
- No guarantee of delivery/order
- Faster, low overhead

👉 Trade-off:
- TCP = reliability
- UDP = speed :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol)

- Runs on top of TCP
- Request-response model
- Stateless

Versions:
- HTTP/1.1 → basic
- HTTP/2 → multiplexing
- HTTP/3 → uses UDP (QUIC)

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 REST (Representational State Transfer)

- Architectural style for APIs
- Uses HTTP methods

Principles:
- Stateless
- Resource-based (URL = resource)
- Client-server separation

Example:
GET /users/1

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 GraphQL

- Query language for APIs
- Client specifies exact data needed

Pros:
- No over-fetching / under-fetching
- Flexible queries

Cons:
- More complex backend

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 gRPC (Google RPC)

- High-performance RPC framework
- Uses Protocol Buffers (binary)
- Runs over HTTP/2

Use:
- Microservices communication

Pros:
- Fast, efficient
- Strong typing

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 SSE (Server-Sent Events)

- Server → client streaming (one-way)
- Uses HTTP connection

Use:
- Live notifications, updates

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 WebSockets (WS)

- Full-duplex communication (bi-directional)
- Persistent connection

Use:
- Chat apps
- Real-time dashboards

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 WebRTC

- Peer-to-peer real-time communication
- Audio, video, data streaming

Use:
- Video calls, conferencing

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Scaling

Vertical Scaling:
- Increase machine size (CPU, RAM)
- Simple but limited

Horizontal Scaling:
- Add more machines
- Highly scalable

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Load Balancing

- Distributes traffic across servers

Types:

1) Client-Side LB:
- Client decides which server to hit

2) Dedicated LB:
- Separate service distributes requests

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 L4 vs L7 Load Balancer

L4 (Transport Layer):
- Works on IP + port
- Faster, less intelligent

L7 (Application Layer):
- Works on HTTP (URL, headers)
- Smarter routing

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Regionalization

- Deploy services in multiple regions
- Reduce latency
- Improve availability

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Reliability Patterns

Timeouts:
- Stop waiting after fixed time

Retries:
- Retry failed requests

Backoff:
- Increase delay between retries

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Cascading Failures

- One service failure → chain reaction

Example:
Service A → B → C (C fails → all fail)

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Circuit Breaker

- Stops repeated calls to failing service

States:
- Closed → normal
- Open → block calls
- Half-open → test recovery

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Key Interview Points

- OSI = abstraction model (not real implementation)
- TCP vs UDP = reliability vs speed trade-off
- HTTP = stateless protocol over TCP
- WebSockets/WebRTC = real-time communication
- Horizontal scaling > vertical scaling
- L4 vs L7 = speed vs intelligence
- Circuit breaker prevents cascading failures

--------------------------------------------------

🧠 One-liner:
Modern distributed systems rely on layered networking (OSI), transport protocols (TCP/UDP), and scalable communication patterns (HTTP, WebSockets, gRPC) with reliability mechanisms like retries and circuit breakers.